The paper deals with a geometric optimization problem involving point sets and matching, which suggests that it belongs to the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The use of flip operations and the study of minimum and maximum lengths of flip sequences suggest that it may also belong to the discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. The mention of spread and convex position of point sets suggests that it may also belong to the computational geometry theory (cs.GT) sub-category. The use of upper bounds and tightness of bounds suggests that it may also belong to the data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the mention of bichromatic matching and spanning trees suggests that it may also belong to the social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
